 from cpuig infoserv com carlos m puig subject re analog switches balanced demodulators organization minimax research corp x newsreader rusnews v zero nine eight lines two six msf skaro as arizona edu michael fulbright writes i am trying to build a synchronous demodulator and i ve hit a snag in my application i want to be able to change the gain of an op amp amplifier from one to one controlable via a digital input the most obvious way i ve come up with is to use analog switches to adjust the gain of the op amp the only analog switch i have experience with it the four zero six six unfortunately i want to switch an ac signal which goes from about five v to five v and the four zero six six is only for positive signals i have recently used the four zero six six to switch a bipolar signal i simply ran the four zero six six off a bipolar supply eight v in this case as long as your analog input signal stays between the supply rails the four zero six six will work fine of course your control logic input must use eight v as the logic low and eight v as the logic high reference so that either one all your driving logic must be four zero zero zero cmos with the same bipolar supply or two you must provide some kind of voltage level shifting circuit between the four zero six six and the control logic in my case i was able to use the bipolar supply all the way carlos puig kj six st cpuig infoserv com san jose ca four zero eight two eight nine eight one seven four